Introduction

Case study

We will use a simulated Individual Patient Data (IPD) meta-analysis with missing values. This dataset is a simulated version of an IPD meta-analysis consisting of 28 studies focusing on risk factors in acute heart failure (GREAT Network, 2013). Managing acute heart failure in the ed - case studies from the acute heart failure academy. http://www.greatnetwork.org). Each study includes a list of patient characteristics and potential risk factors. Each of them is incomplete, leading to sporadically missing values (Resche-Rigon, et al 2013). In addition, some variables have been collected on some studies only, leading to systematically missing values. More details on the original dataset are provided in Audigier et al. (2018). To mimic the real data, a general location model has been fitted on each study (Schafer, 1997). Then, each study has been generated according to the estimated parameters. Finally, missing values have been allocated similarly to the original dataset.

Prerequisites

We first load the necessary packages

library(MASS)
library(reshape2)
library(ggplot2)
library(mice)
library(micemd)
library(mitml)
library(jomo)
library(lme4)
library(dplyr)
library(metafor)

Configuration

set.seed(113393)

# parameters
main_fmla <- "lvef ~ bnp + afib"
main_fmla_1stage <- "lvef ~ bnp + afib + (bnp|centre)"
var_monitor <- c("bmi", "bnp","afib")
n_burnin <- 10000
n_between <- 5000
n_impute <- 10 # how many imputed datasets to generate?
maxit_impute <- 20

GREAT data

The GREAT data contains 11685 observations on the following 10 variables.

  • centre: a numeric indexing the center where the study is conducted
  • gender: a factor with levels 0 1
  • bmi: a numeric vector indicating the body mass index
  • age: a numeric vector indicating the age
  • sbp: a numeric vector indicating the systolic blood pressure
  • dbp: a numeric vector indicating the diastolic blood pressure
  • hr: a numeric vector indicating the heart rate
  • lvef: a numeric vector indicating the ventricular ejection fraction
  • bnp: a numeric vector indicating the level of the brain natriuretic peptide biomarker
  • afib: a factor with levels 0 1 indicating the atrial fibrillation
data(IPDNa)
by(IPDNa,IPDNa$centre,summary)

Results

Complete case analysis (2-stage)

centres <- unique(IPDNa$centre)
estimates <- data.frame(array(NA, dim=c(length(centres),2)))
colnames(estimates) <- c("beta.bnp", "se.beta.bnp")
for (i in 1:length(centres)) {
  stdat <- subset(IPDNa, centre==centres[i])
  stdat <- stdat [complete.cases(stdat), ]
  stdat$gender <- as.numeric(stdat$gender)-1
  stdat$afib <- as.numeric(stdat$afib)-1
  stdat <- as.data.frame(stdat)
  
  if (nrow(stdat)>2) {
    fit <- glm(main_fmla, data = stdat)
    estimates$beta.bnp[i] <- coefficients(fit)["bnp"]
    
    if (!is.na(coefficients(fit)["bnp"])) {
      estimates$se.beta.bnp[i] <- sqrt(vcov(fit)[match("bnp", names(coefficients(fit))),match("bnp", names(coefficients(fit)))])
    }
  }
}
estimates <- subset(estimates, !is.na(beta.bnp))

rma(yi=estimates$beta.bnp, sei=estimates$se.beta.bnp, method="REML",test="knha")

Multiple imputation using FCS-2stage

We here adopt two-stage imputation that accounts for between-study heterogeneity in the intercept term, and the effect of BNP.

# a. CONSTRUCT THE PREDICTOR MATIRX
pred <- imp1l$predict
pred[,"bnp"] <- 2
pred["bnp",] <- 2
pred[,"centre"] <- -2
pred[c("centre", "gender", "lvef"),] <- 0
diag(pred) <- 0
print(pred)

Multiple imputation using JOMO (common covariance)

# c. Fit imputation model with common covariance matrix
if (!file.exists("../Data/great_impjm_common.RData") | refit) {
  impjm_common <- jomoImpute(formula = as.formula("bmi+age+sbp+dbp+hr+bnp+afib~gender+lvef+(1|centre)"), 
                       random.L1 = "none", 
                       m = n_impute,
                       data = IPDNa, 
                       n.burn = n_burnin, 
                       n.iter = n_between)
  save(impjm_common, file="../Data/great_impjm_common.RData")
  
  # Put results in a list in mitml format
  implist <- mitmlComplete(impjm_common, print=1:n_impute)
  
  # This is to fit analysis model on each imp
  midsjm_common <- with(implist, lmer("lvef ~ bnp + afib + (bnp|centre)")) 
  save(midsjm_common, file="../Data/great_midsjm_common.RData")
} else {
  load(file = "../Data/great_impjm_common.RData")
  load(file = "../Data/great_midsjm_common.RData")
}

We can monitor convergence by analyzing the difference between multiple Markov chains. The convergence is assessed by comparing the estimated between-chains and within-chain variances for each model parameter. Large differences between these variances indicate nonconvergence. The potential scale reduction factor (PSRF) is defined as the ratio of the pooled variance (i.e. the total of the within- and between-chains variances) over the within-chain variance. The PSRF should be near 1 in case of convergence, and will be greater than 1 in case of non-convergence. Because JOMO only uses a single Markov chain, the PRSFs are computed by dividing each chain from the imputation phase into a number of sequences (3 by default).

The estimated potential scale reduction factor for each model parameter are given below

We can evaluate convergence as follows

When inspecting convergence, it can be seen that a couple of parameters have not yet converged, which is likely given how many covariance matrix parameters we have with this model. (this should be around 3088/2). Although this may not much have affected the results, increasing the number of iterations may be preferred.
